---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Section from "../components/Section.astro";
import NetworkAtlas from "../components/NetworkAtlas.astro";
import NetworkArchitecture from "../components/NetworkArchitecture.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<Layout title="Network" description="A co-presence map of named characters across the seventy-three episodes.">
  <Nav slot="nav" />

  <Section>
    <div class="page-head reveal visible">
      <p class="eyebrow">03</p>
      <h1>Character co-presence</h1>
      <div class="page-lede">
        <p>
          One hundred and thirty named characters appear across the seventy-three
          episodes. This page maps their co-presence — which characters share
          episodes, how often they recur, and where communities form — using
          public-safe exports from the 2D character network analysis.
        </p>
        <p>
          Co-occurrence is not interaction. Two characters sharing an episode does
          not mean they meet, speak, or act together. What the network shows is
          structural proximity: characters the novel places in the same formal
          unit, weighted by how often that placement recurs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section>
    <div class="figure-block reveal visible">
      <figure class="network-figure">
        <NetworkAtlas />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="figure-id">Fig. 1.</span> Master character network atlas.
          Each node is a named character; edges connect characters who share at
          least one episode. Node size reflects weighted degree (frequency-adjusted
          co-presence). Colour marks community assignment: five detected communities
          loosely correspond to the London–Counterforce cluster, the Quest and
          Transition group around Slothrop, the Rocket System cluster around
          Blicero and Enzian, the Pökler Island group, and a small Late Afterlives
          set. Hover or click a node to explore its connections.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section narrow={true}>
    <div class="prose-block reveal visible">
      <p>
        The atlas is dominated by Slothrop, who touches forty-six of the
        seventy-three episodes and links to all five communities. His
        betweenness centrality (0.83) reflects his structural role as a bridge
        across the novel's social space. The next most central characters —
        Pointsman and Roger Mexico in the London Counterforce cluster,
        Blicero and Enzian in the Rocket System — remain well connected
        to Slothrop's neighbourhood.
      </p>
      <p>
        Community detection finds five groups. The London Counterforce cluster
        (Pointsman, Roger, Jessica, Pirate) is dense and tightly bounded. The
        Rocket System cluster (Blicero, Enzian, Tchitcherine, Gottfried) is
        sparser but stretches further. The Quest and Transition group
        gathers Slothrop's recurring co-presences across the middle episodes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section>
    <div class="figure-block reveal visible">
      <figure class="network-figure">
        <NetworkArchitecture />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="figure-id">Fig. 2.</span> Network architecture. A
          three-panel view of the co-presence network's structural properties.
          The figure argues that the novel's social geometry is distributed rather
          than hub-and-spoke: while Slothrop is the highest-degree node, the
          network retains coherence if he is removed, held together by secondary
          bridge characters across communities.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section narrow={true}>
    <div class="notes-block reveal visible">
      <p class="eyebrow">Notes</p>
      <ol class="notes-list">
        <li>
          The network is built from episode-level co-occurrence counts exported
          as public-safe CSVs. Edge weights use association strength (a
          normalised co-occurrence measure) rather than raw counts. Community
          detection uses the Louvain algorithm.
        </li>
        <li>
          Both figures draw only on the public-safe data layer. The underlying
          node and edge tables are available in the
          <a href="https://github.com/dinghaoluo/the_zone_site">source
          repository</a> under <code>public/data/step_2d/</code>.
          Static reference versions of the original figures are available for download:
          <a href={`${base}/figures/step_2d/F06_master_character_network_atlas.svg`}>atlas (SVG)</a>,
          <a href={`${base}/figures/step_2d/F05_network_architecture_flagship.svg`}>architecture (SVG)</a>.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Footer slot="footer" />
</Layout>

<style>
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3.5vw, 2.5rem);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
  }

  .page-lede {
    max-width: var(--max-width-narrow);
  }

  .page-lede p {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .figure-block {
    max-width: var(--max-width);
  }

  .network-figure {
    margin: 0;
  }

  figcaption {
    margin-top: var(--space-md);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--color-text-dim);
    max-width: var(--max-width-narrow);
  }

  .figure-id {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-dim);
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;
  }

  .prose-block p {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    max-width: var(--max-width-narrow);
  }

  .notes-block {
    padding-top: var(--space-md);
  }

  .notes-list {
    margin-top: var(--space-lg);
    padding-left: 1.5em;
    list-style: decimal;
  }

  .notes-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--color-text-dim);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .notes-list li a {
    color: var(--color-accent-dim);
  }

  .notes-list li a:hover {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .notes-list code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }
</style>
